        <section id="background">
            <div class="container">
                <h2>Background</h2>
                <div class="divider"></div>
                <p>Every day, Canada sees over 350 new cases of neurodegenerative diseases, like Alzheimer’s Disease (AD), impacting lives across the country [1]. There is then an urgent need to improve neurovascular health, and a significant step towards this goal is the early detection of neurodegenerative diseases. Current technologies, however, lack the sensitivity necessary for early detection, and the process for differential diagnosis is also often hindered by the absence of definitive diagnostic standards. In contrast to traditional diagnostic methods, our biosensor aims limits exposure of patients to high levels of radiation through computed tomography (CT) and Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) scans. [2] The focus of this research aims to create a modular biosensor that is not only highly sensitive but selective towards target biomarkers. </p><br>
                <p>DNADetect will consist of DNA origami nanopores inserted into Large Unilamellar Vesicles that encapsulates fluorescent dye molecules. Inside the Nanopore lumen, there is a linker strand that holds to an aptazyme component, hindering any molecules from flowing through. In the presence of a biomarker, the aptazyme self-cleaves upon binding and dissociates from the nanopore. The opening of the nanopore lumen then increases, allowing dye molecules to diffuse out of the vesicles. A noticeable change in fluorescence should then be detected, providing the optical signal that a neurodegenerative disease biomarker is present.</p><br>
                <p>The selectivity of DNADetect is achieved through the aptazyme component. The aptazyme consists of a specific RNA sequence that folds into a pocket that binds only to a specific molecule. This ensures highly specific interactions regardless of the surrounding matrix solution. The biosensor is able to exhibit high sensitivity through its ability to induce a fluorescent change with the presence of just one target molecule that enables the cleavage reaction. This enables the biosensor to operate even at low concentrations of the biomarker.</p> <br>
                <h3>Research Questions</h3>
                <div class="subtitle-divider"></div>
                <p class="flow-text">
                    1. How can we create a solution that is highly sensitive for early detection of neurodegenerative diseases?
                    <br>2. How can we design a modular biosensor that is suitable for detecting various biomarkers found in neurodegenerative diseases?
                    <br>3. What minimally invasive diagnostic techniques for neurodegenerative diseases could be employed to reduce patient exposure to radiation?
                </p>
            </div>
